# Real-Time & WebSocket Patterns

Coding patterns for real-time features. IF your project has real-time features or any server-to-client push - apply these patterns.

> This file defines HOW to implement real-time communication, not WHAT features to build. The patterns apply to any server-to-client push scenario.

All numeric values (connection limits, heartbeat intervals, timeouts) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## When to Use Real-Time

**Principle:** Choose the simplest real-time transport that meets your latency and bidirectionality requirements.

[REFERENCE] Transport selection guide:

| Use Case | Approach |
|----------|----------|
| Two-way communication (client sends + receives) | WebSocket (persistent connection) |
| Server pushes updates, client only listens | SSE (Server-Sent Events) - simpler, auto-reconnects |
| Infrequent updates (< once per minute) | Polling or long-polling |
| One-time request/response | Standard HTTP - don't over-engineer with WebSocket |
| Data that changes every few minutes | Polling (30-60s) or SSE |
| Static content | Normal HTTP - no real-time needed |

**Rule**: Don't use WebSockets where HTTP polling or Server-Sent Events (SSE) would suffice. WebSockets add complexity - earn that complexity.

### Event naming test

Name events **`resource:action`** (e.g. `message:created`, `order:statusChanged`). Payload carries ids and deltas - not full unauthorized records.

### Feature Flag for Real-Time

Real-time features should be globally toggleable without redeploying:

```
Pattern:
  1. Store a "live updates enabled" flag in config/DB/env
  2. Server: check flag before setting up WebSocket listeners
  3. Client: check flag before attempting connection (skip entirely if disabled)
  4. Gracefully degrade - show static data with manual refresh when real-time is off
```

This lets you disable real-time during incidents, high load, or when the feature isn't needed.

