## Real-Time Event Flow (Generic Pattern)

Every real-time feature follows this flow:

```
Client Action -> Server:
  1. Client emits event with payload
  2. Server authenticates (from socket session, NEVER trust client-provided identity)
  3. Server validates payload (same rules as REST: type, length, permissions)
  4. Server persists to database
  5. Server broadcasts to relevant room(s)
  6. Server triggers side effects (outbound webhooks, job queues) if needed

Server Update -> Client:
  1. Client receives event
  2. Client updates local state (optimistic UI already shown, or append new data)
  3. Client acknowledges if needed (acknowledgment patterns, sync confirmations)

Mutations (Edit / Delete):
  1. Server enforces access and permission checks
  2. Server persists change
  3. Server broadcasts update/delete event to room
  4. Clients update their local state accordingly
```

### Activity Indicators

```
  1. Client emits "activity:start" when user begins an activity (editing, viewing, drawing, etc.)
  2. Server broadcasts "activity:active" to other room members
  3. Client debounce: don't emit more than once per 2 seconds
  4. Client emits "activity:stop" when activity ends (3 second timeout)
  5. Server broadcasts "activity:inactive"
  6. Client auto-clears activity indicator after 5 seconds (safety net)
  7. Auto-clear "Someone is active..." after 10-15 seconds of no new activity events (users pause - don't be too aggressive)
```

### Acknowledgment patterns

```
  1. When user focuses a channel, emit "entity:ack" with { channelId, lastSeenSequence }
  2. Server updates acknowledgment cursor in database
  3. Server broadcasts "entity:ack" to publisher (optional visibility)
  4. Batch acknowledgments - don't emit per row; emit per channel with the latest cursor
```

